<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06190090 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06190090 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Luz International Ltd., the world's largest solar energy producer, laid off350 full-time employees -- half its work force -- and canceled plans to builda new power plant in the Mojave Desert. Citing the recession and cheaperprices for competing oil, the company said it also had laid off 300 temporaryconstruction workers hired last month to build the new plant. TheWestwood-based company accounts for about 90 percent of the world's solarpower production.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SOLAR FIRM CUTS JOBS, CANCELS PLANT  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910708  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  78  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday July 8, 199100190090,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>